{{Infobox venue | name = Arctic Winter Games Arena | image = | image_caption = | nickname = | address = | location = [[Iqaluit]], [[Nunavut]], Canada | pushpin_map = Canada Nunavut | pushpin_mapsize = | pushpin_map_caption = Location in Nunavut | pushpin_label_position = | coordinates = {{coord|63|44|24|N|68|28|42|W|type:landmark_region:CA-NU|display=title}} | type = Ice arena | genre = | built = | opened = October 2001 | renovated = 2009<ref name="2mil renovation" /> | expanded = | closed = | demolished = | owner = | construction_cost= | former_names = | seating_type = | seating_capacity = 2,500 | website = }}
The '''Arctic Winter Games Arena''' is a 2,500-seat multi-purpose [[arena]] in [[Iqaluit]], [[Nunavut]], Canada. It opened to the public in October 2001.<ref>http://www.nnsl.com/frames/newspapers/2010-10/oct18_10awg.html</ref> This arena was initially constructed to house the hockey and speed skating events of the 2002 [[Arctic Winter Games]], but it is now used as a youth centre and to host large community events.
The venue hosted [[CBC Television]]'s [[Hockey Day in Canada]] in 2003,<ref name="Hockey night in Canada">{{cite news|url=http://www.nunatsiaq.com/archives/nunavut030221/news/features/30221_02.html|title=Hockey Day in Iqaluit|last=Murphy|first=Kirsten|date=2003-02-21|work=Nunatsiaq News|accessdate=2009-09-03}}</ref> and a [[White Stripes]] concert in 2007.<ref name="white stripes">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/entertainment/article/230218|title=Iqaluit welcomes Stripes with open arms|authorlink=Ben Rayner|last=Rayner|first=Ben|date=2007-07-28|work=Toronto Star|accessdate=2009-09-03}}</ref> The arena was also site to four professional wrestling events, featuring WWE superstars [[Christian (wrestler)|Christian]] and [[Gail Kim]], as well as [[Tracy Brooks]], [[Robert Roode]] and [[Rhino (wrestler)|Rhino]] in 2008.
The surface of the arena had become unusable (for ice) after a portion the floor sank in 2006,<ref name="floor fails">{{cite news|url=http://nnsl.com/northern-news-services/stories/papers/feb9_09ah.html |title=Iqaluit looks ahead |last=Zarate |first=Gabriel |work=Northern News Services |accessdate=2009-09-03 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110714190449/http://nnsl.com/northern-news-services/stories/papers/feb9_09ah.html |archivedate=2011-07-14 }}</ref> however, on August 18, 2009, $2.2&nbsp;million was allocated by the [[Government of Canada]] to repair the surface.<ref name="2mil renovation">{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/article/682491|title=$50M for Arctic development|last=Campion-Smith|first=Bruce|date=2009-08-18|work=[[Toronto Star]]|accessdate=2009-09-03}}</ref>
