{{Infobox stadium | coordinates = {{Coord|60|26|33|N|022|15|39|E|region:FI-19_type:landmark|display=it}} | image = Kalevan Kisat 2011 Turussa (Finnish Championships in Athletics 2011 in Turku).jpg | image_size = 250px | caption = 2011 Finnish Championships in Athletics at Paavo Nurmi Stadium | location=[[Turku]], [[Finland]] | owner = City of Turku | operator = City of Turku | seating_capacity=13,000 | opened=1890s | renovated=1997 | website = [https://web.archive.org/web/20130929013457/http://www.turku.fi/Public/default.aspx?contentid=29090 www.turku.fi/...] }} '''Paavo Nurmi Stadium''' ({{lang-fi|Paavo Nurmen stadion}}, {{lang-sv|Paavo Nurmis stadion}}) is a multi-use [[stadium]] in [[Turku]], [[Finland]]. It is currently used mostly for [[football (soccer)|football]] matches and [[Athletics (track and field)|athletics]] meets. It holds 13,000 people and is named after the Turku-born runner [[Paavo Nurmi]]. Twenty athletics world records have been set at the stadium.<ref name="TS">{{cite news | first=Tuomas | last=Rimpiläinen | newspaper=[[Turun Sanomat]] | title=Turkuun pystytettiin kirjoitusvirheitä pursuava muistomerkki | date=6 October 2010 | url=http://www.ts.fi/uutiset/kotimaa/164223/Turkuun+pystytettiin+kirjoitusvirheita+pursuava+muistomerkki | accessdate=20 September 2012 | language=Finnish}}</ref> [[John Landy]] broke the world records for the 1,500 m and the mile (1954), Nurmi for the 3,000 m (1922), [[Emil Zátopek]] (1950) and [[Ron Clarke]] (1965) for the 10,000 m, [[Viljo Heino]] for the one-hour run (1945) and the 20&nbsp;km (1949), [[Matti Järvinen]] for the javelin throw (1932) and [[Charles Hoff]] for the pole vault (1925).<ref name="TS"/>
[[Paavo Nurmi Games]], a track and field meet, is held at the stadium annually.
